#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""RQ4 (paid, LLM-judged): does retrieving the right skill actually improve
downstream task performance?

This is the paid counterpart to rq4_free_lexical_proxy.py. Where the free
proxy asks a zero-cost lexical question ("does the injected skill's text
even look relevant to the oracle solution?"), this script asks the real
question by actually calling an LLM to (a) attempt the task under each
retrieval condition and (b) judge, against the task's oracle solution and
verifier criteria, whether that attempt would pass.

Design choices, and why:

- Conditions match rq4_free_lexical_proxy.py's DEFAULT_CONDITIONS exactly
  (no_skill, gold_skill, retrieved_top1_full, hard_distractor, random_wrong)
  so the two experiments are directly comparable.
- Retrieval always ranks over the FULL 34k-skill library (not a sampled
  pool), matching the user's requirement and mirroring how RQ1 treats the
  "full" pool size.
- repeats defaults to 1. This mirrors RQ1's own convention: RQ1 already
  drops to a single repeat once the pool size is "full", because at full
  library size there is nothing left to resample except random_wrong. RQ4
  always operates at full-library size, so repeats=1 is the consistent
  choice, and it is also the affordable choice under a small token budget.
  Raise --repeats later (e.g. to match RQ3's 3) once budget allows; only
  random_wrong actually changes across repeats.
- Skill context given to the solver is name + description only (the same
  fields RQ1-RQ3's primary bm25_desc condition used), NOT the full
  SKILL.md body. This means skills-34k/skills.zip does NOT need to be
  unzipped for this script -- skills_meta.jsonl is enough. It also keeps
  the prompt (and therefore token cost) small.
- Because there is no sandboxed execution environment here, "does it pass"
  is approximated by an LLM judge that reads the task's oracle solution
  and verifier text and grades the solver's proposed solution against
  them. This is a judged-pass proxy for real task pass/fail, not a
  replacement for actually running SkillsBench/Terminal-Bench tasks in a
  sandbox. State this limitation whenever reporting results from this
  script, the same way rq4_downstream_skill_exposure.py documents its own
  "not actual agent pass rate" boundary.

Cost control:
- --limit-tasks defaults to 5. You must pass a larger number (or 0 for all
  tasks) explicitly once you're happy with a small-scale test.
- --dry-run builds every prompt and estimates token counts WITHOUT calling
  the API, so you can sanity check cost before spending anything.
- A running token counter is persisted to <output-dir>/token_usage_state.json
  and checked against --token-budget before every pair of calls, so a
  multi-session run can't blow through your budget even if you forget to
  raise the limit.
- Results are written incrementally to per_task_results.jsonl (append mode)
  so a killed/interrupted run doesn't lose progress; rerun with
  --resume to skip (task, condition, repeat) rows already recorded.

Usage (PowerShell), small scale:
  $env:DASHSCOPE_API_KEY = "sk-xxxx"
  python rq4_downstream_task_performance.py --limit-tasks 3 --dry-run
  python rq4_downstream_task_performance.py --limit-tasks 3 --model qwen-plus
"""

